# CEM — Decision Records Stage Specification

This document defines the Decision Records stage as a general, reusable part of the CEM pipeline. It sits
between Requirements and System Architecture, and is domain-independent in the same sense the Requirements
spec is — the same rules apply whether the decision is which battery chemistry to use, which library to
import, or which vendor to contract.

```
Requirements
    │
    ▼
Decision Records   ← this document
    │
    ▼
System Architecture
```

## 1. Purpose

Requirements asks: *what needs to be decided?*
Decision Records asks: *why did we choose this, and how do we know we chose correctly?*

A Decision Record is the moment a Requirements row's flags (Performance, Interface, Constraint, Make-vs-Buy)
get matched against real-world candidates, a choice gets made, and the reasoning — along with what it would
take to trust that choice — is kept. It is not the implementation detail itself; that's System Architecture's
job, and only gets written once a Decision Record reaches its final lifecycle state.

## 2. Scope

A Requirements row may have **one or more** Decision Records over its life. Most rows will have exactly one.
A row gets a second Decision Record when the first one is invalidated by something outside the project's
control — a part goes obsolete, a regulation changes, a vendor disappears — not by editing the original
record, but by creating a new one and linking it (see §7, Supersession). Nothing is deleted; the old record
stays in history, same as a superseded Concept Architecture version.

## 3. Decision ID

Every Decision Record is identified by a **Decision ID**, structured as `DR:<Node ID>:<sequence>`
(e.g. `DR:PWR.RECHG.CTRL:001`). The sequence number increments if a node is ever re-decided. Decision IDs are
the reference a Requirements row's Status field points to once a decision exists for it.

## 4. Fields

| Field | Required | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| Decision ID | Yes | `DR:<Node ID>:<sequence>` |
| Node ID | Yes | Back-reference to the Requirements row this resolves |
| Concept Version | Yes | Copied from the Requirements row at time of decision — lets you detect if the decision was made against a since-superseded structure |
| Candidates Considered | Yes | Every option actually examined, not just the winner |
| Criteria Used | Yes | Which dimensions mattered for comparison — typically drawn from the row's Performance/Interface/Constraint/Make-vs-Buy flags, plus anything else that mattered (lead time, vendor relationship, etc.) |
| Chosen | Yes | The selected candidate |
| Reason | Yes | One-line rationale — why this candidate over the others |
| Reversibility Note | Yes | What breaks, and where, if this decision is later reversed |
| Evidence Required | Yes | Checklist of what must be true before the decision is trusted (see §5) |
| Decision Status | Yes | Lifecycle state (see §6) |
| Author / Date | Yes | Who decided, when |
| Supersedes / Superseded By | Conditional | Links to the prior/next Decision Record for this Node ID, if any |

## 5. Evidence Required

A checklist of what has to be true before this decision is considered trustworthy — e.g. Datasheet, Test
Result, CAD Model, Simulation, Certification, Customer Approval. Items are chosen per decision, not fixed
per node type.

This field belongs here, not in Requirements, because it describes the chosen solution, not the abstract
need. At the Requirements stage there is nothing yet to demand proof about; "Evidence Required" only becomes
meaningful once a specific candidate has been named as Chosen.

## 6. Decision Status (lifecycle)

```
Open
  │
  ▼
Candidate Evaluation
  │
  ▼
Selected
  │
  ▼
Evidence Collected
  │
  ▼
Verified
  │
  ▼
Released
```

| State | Meaning |
|---|---|
| **Open** | Row has been picked up from Requirements; no candidates gathered yet |
| **Candidate Evaluation** | Candidates are being compared against Criteria Used |
| **Selected** | Chosen is populated, Reason is written — but nothing has been proven yet |
| **Evidence Collected** | Items in Evidence Required have been gathered |
| **Verified** | Collected evidence has been reviewed and confirmed sufficient |
| **Released** | Decision is final; System Architecture may now record the implementation detail |

A Decision Record only feeds System Architecture once it reaches **Released**. Nothing upstream of that state
should be treated as settled, even if a candidate has been named.

## 7. Supersession

If a Released decision is later invalidated by something external to the project, the response is a **new**
Decision Record, not an edit to the old one:

- The new record gets the next sequence number for that Node ID (`DR:PWR.SUPPLY.BATT:002`).
- The old record's `Superseded By` field points to the new one; the new record's `Supersedes` field points back.
- The old record is left exactly as it was — it remains an accurate account of what was true and decided at
  the time. Nothing about supersession implies the original decision was wrong given what was known then.

## 8. Handoff to System Architecture

Once a Decision Record reaches **Released**, System Architecture records the actual implementation detail for
the Chosen candidate — part number, pinout, library version, or equivalent. System Architecture never makes a
choice itself; it only documents the outcome of a Released Decision Record. If a decision is later superseded,
System Architecture is updated to match the new Released record, and the change traces cleanly back through
both Decision Records to the Requirements row that started it.
